01:21.280 --> 01:22.430
[GASPS]

01:22.640 --> 01:23.640
Oh!

01:23.800 --> 01:26.235
Waiting for Walter?
Mrs. McCallam.

01:26.440 --> 01:29.399
He's running a little late,
and I just couldn't bear
the thought of you

01:29.600 --> 01:32.115
sitting here all alone,
so I came to keep you company.

01:32.320 --> 01:34.471
Well, I'm not waiting for Walter.
Save it.

01:34.680 --> 01:37.036
Waiter, a martini.

01:37.240 --> 01:38.754
I want you to stop seeing him.

01:39.320 --> 01:40.879
Uh, the waiter?

01:41.080 --> 01:43.436
No. Walter.

01:43.640 --> 01:45.757
Oh, I don't know
what you're talking about.

01:45.960 --> 01:47.792
You and my husband.

01:48.000 --> 01:50.993
The Standish Hotel in Boston,
The Ritz Hotel in Hartford,

01:51.200 --> 01:54.876
The Plaza Hotel in New York,
the Trafalgar Hotel in New Haven.

01:55.080 --> 01:59.438
Not New Haven.
We were never in...
Never in New Haven.

01:59.640 --> 02:02.997
All right, now that we've
gotten that out of the way,
I want you to stop seeing him.

02:03.200 --> 02:04.919
No, I won't.
We love each other.

02:05.120 --> 02:08.157
Oh, please. Love?
Walter doesn't love anyone.

02:08.360 --> 02:12.434
Walter is the most totally
self-absorbed person in the world.

02:12.640 --> 02:15.838
We have a 7-year-old daughter,
Abigail. Walter calls her Amanda.

02:16.080 --> 02:18.515
Seven years and he still
doesn't know her name.

02:18.720 --> 02:19.915
Thank you.

02:20.120 --> 02:25.195
So do you bow out gracefully,
or do I tell Walter to dump you?

02:25.400 --> 02:28.757
Are you kidding?
Walter would never dump me.

02:37.600 --> 02:38.750
Guess you spotted me.

02:41.120 --> 02:42.998
We were just talking about you.

02:43.200 --> 02:44.236
Small world.

02:44.440 --> 02:47.201
Imagine the three of us
running into each other
in the same restaurant.

02:47.280 --> 02:48.280
Don't bother, Walter.

02:48.480 --> 02:50.312
Bother? It's no bother.
It's no bother at all.

02:50.520 --> 02:51.954
She knows, darling.
She knows?

02:53.480 --> 02:54.834
Ah.

02:55.480 --> 02:59.394
Yes. And I was just telling Eunice
that if you had to make a choice

02:59.600 --> 03:01.478
between the two of us,
I know you'd choose me.

03:01.680 --> 03:04.957
You see, I took out a small
insurance policy, a detective,

03:05.160 --> 03:08.153
who, among other things,
discovered that you were
being blackmailed.

03:08.400 --> 03:12.235
I paid the blackmailer
and bought the most
interesting set of pictures.

03:12.440 --> 03:14.281
By the way, darling,
you don't photograph well.

03:15.640 --> 03:18.712
Now, should you ever
see her again,

03:18.920 --> 03:22.436
I will give those negatives
to the press.

03:23.240 --> 03:25.709
You'd do that?
I mean, you'd ruin my career?

03:25.920 --> 03:26.920
That's right.

03:27.080 --> 03:29.470
You don't need a career,
darling. I'll support us.

03:29.680 --> 03:31.751
You'd see to it that I never
held any office again?

03:31.960 --> 03:33.713
Correct.
We could go away.

03:33.920 --> 03:35.718
No money, no job, no nothing?

03:35.960 --> 03:37.713
Uh-huh.
We'd have each other.

03:37.920 --> 03:39.070
Eunice?
Yes?

03:39.840 --> 03:41.638
See you.

03:42.840 --> 03:44.797
[♪♪♪]

04:07.720 --> 04:09.200
Mom...

04:09.400 --> 04:13.235
It's all my fault. I sent him here.
He didn't want to come.

04:13.440 --> 04:14.999
Ma, come on.
He had to come.

04:15.200 --> 04:17.668
No. No, he didn't.
And now look what's happened.

04:17.880 --> 04:20.315
He's run away
and God knows where he is.

04:20.519 --> 04:23.035
[IN HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]
Makes it hard to sleep at night
knowing lunatics come and go

04:23.240 --> 04:24.321
as they please around here.

04:24.480 --> 04:26.119
Listen, you...

04:26.560 --> 04:28.313
Ma, I got your message.
What happened?

04:28.520 --> 04:32.036
Burt's missing.
They checked all the rooms
at bedtime and he wasn't there.

04:32.240 --> 04:34.516
He never was, if you know
what I mean. Ha-ha-ha!

04:35.080 --> 04:36.753
No, Mom, Mom.

04:38.720 --> 04:40.234
How long has he been gone?

04:40.440 --> 04:43.353
Hours. It's all my fault.
I feel so awful.

04:43.560 --> 04:45.438
My God, what if
he never comes home?

04:45.640 --> 04:47.233
Drinks are on me.

04:50.200 --> 04:51.429
MARY:
Stop it.

04:51.640 --> 04:54.314
Stop it. Boys, stop it!

05:02.240 --> 05:04.630
Boys, boys, boys.

05:04.840 --> 05:07.833
Lights were out
over an hour ago.
Back to your rooms.

05:08.040 --> 05:10.111
We're just visiting.
You're visiting?

05:10.320 --> 05:12.994
Two men attack a wooden doll
while the third screams?

05:13.200 --> 05:14.200
Nice try.

05:14.400 --> 05:15.720
See, you don't understand.

05:15.920 --> 05:18.560
Bob here was saying
some really nasty things.

05:18.760 --> 05:20.274
Oh, yeah?
Yeah.

05:20.480 --> 05:22.073
Danny, Danny, not here.

05:22.280 --> 05:24.590
Oh, I see.

05:24.800 --> 05:27.190
The doll said something nasty,

05:27.400 --> 05:29.995
so you wanted to kill it.

05:32.440 --> 05:34.113
They're visitors, doctor.

05:34.320 --> 05:35.674
Who are you?
Their mother.

05:35.880 --> 05:37.712
I'm sorry.

05:38.520 --> 05:40.079
We have visitor's passes.

05:41.080 --> 05:43.595
Visiting hours are over.
You'll have to leave.

05:43.800 --> 05:46.395
You see, we're waiting
for my husband. He ran away.

05:46.600 --> 05:48.353
I don't blame him.

05:49.400 --> 05:50.914
Keep the noise down.

05:51.120 --> 05:54.397
And try and set an example
for the patients.

05:58.200 --> 06:01.830
I'm sorry.
That's okay, Dan.

06:20.440 --> 06:22.671
Hey, Mare, how are you doing...?

06:25.720 --> 06:27.552
Where were you?
We were so worried.

06:27.760 --> 06:29.831
I didn't do anything.
Yeah, are you all right?

06:30.040 --> 06:31.713
I'm fine. I'm okay.

06:31.920 --> 06:34.196
You boys wait downstairs for me.

06:34.400 --> 06:36.915
And no more fighting.
Okay.

06:39.840 --> 06:41.433
Are you all right?
What happened?

06:43.280 --> 06:44.680
I ran away.

06:44.880 --> 06:48.476
Burt, is it so awful here?
Do you hate it that much?

06:48.680 --> 06:50.911
No, no, no, Mary.
It's not awful at all.

06:51.120 --> 06:53.112
It's very nice here
and I'm getting better.

06:53.320 --> 06:55.551
I really am. I'm getting...
I'm getting better.

06:55.760 --> 06:57.319
Then what is it?

06:57.520 --> 07:02.834
You see, Mare, we talk a lot here
and we tell our secrets, you know.

07:03.040 --> 07:05.509
And at first I thought,
"Hey, forget about it."

07:05.720 --> 07:07.279
Nobody's gonna hear my secrets,

07:07.480 --> 07:09.517
because I got some
very weird secrets.

07:09.720 --> 07:13.111
That was until I heard
their secrets.

07:13.320 --> 07:14.436
Worse.

07:14.640 --> 07:16.597
They're mostly the same.

07:16.800 --> 07:20.032
See, we all have
the same secrets.

07:20.520 --> 07:22.432
I mean, they come out
a little different,

07:22.640 --> 07:26.270
and I don't know,
maybe there are one or two here

07:26.480 --> 07:29.598
who, frankly, are a little more creative
in the way they look at the world,

07:29.800 --> 07:32.440
like chicken man, for instance,
but, essentially...

07:33.960 --> 07:35.189
Chicken man?

07:35.400 --> 07:40.316
Yeah. When things get rough,
he becomes a chicken.

07:41.160 --> 07:42.355
Oh.

07:42.560 --> 07:44.358
When things get too
rough with me, I...

07:44.560 --> 07:46.074
Then disappear and...

07:46.280 --> 07:48.840
You know, Harold wears hats,
some people drink a lot,

07:49.040 --> 07:50.997
others sleep,
and, you know, and...

07:51.640 --> 07:54.360
See, I mean, we all have
our own ways

07:54.560 --> 07:56.711
of stepping back
when things get too rough.

07:56.920 --> 08:00.357
In that way, Mare,
we're all the same.

08:00.560 --> 08:02.916
I eat.
Yeah.

08:03.520 --> 08:05.716
See, but then I realised
that I had one secret

08:05.920 --> 08:08.230
that nobody else had,
and unless I told them the secret,

08:08.440 --> 08:09.874
I couldn't really get better.

08:10.080 --> 08:12.834
And unless I told you the secret,
I couldn't come home.

08:13.040 --> 08:17.080
See, because, Mary,
I can't live with you and love you

08:17.800 --> 08:19.234
and keep the secret from you.

08:19.440 --> 08:21.193
So tell me, darling.
Tell me the secret.

08:21.400 --> 08:23.073
I can't, Mary.
That's why I ran away.

08:23.280 --> 08:26.671
Because I realised I can't tell you
the secret, so I can't go home.

08:27.680 --> 08:30.957
Then I thought,
"I can't tell the secret here,
so I can't stay here."

08:31.160 --> 08:33.072
So I ran away,

08:33.280 --> 08:36.159
and I roamed around the city
all night in the subway.

08:36.360 --> 08:40.354
On the subway,
I could have told my secret,
nobody would have cared.

08:41.120 --> 08:42.793
But you came back here.

08:43.000 --> 08:44.673
Mary, I can't live
on the subway.

08:44.880 --> 08:45.880
Ah.

08:46.040 --> 08:48.350
So I figure
I can tell the secret here,

08:48.560 --> 08:52.759
except, of course,
I don't want to live here.
Mary, I got no place to go.

08:52.960 --> 08:55.236
So, darling, tell me
the secret and come home.

08:55.440 --> 08:58.239
I can't. I gotta go.
I don't know where
I'm going, but I gotta go.

08:58.440 --> 09:00.636
Burt. I love you.
What?

09:00.840 --> 09:04.356
You are the most important
thing in my life to me.

09:04.560 --> 09:06.870
So there is nothing,
absolutely nothing,

09:07.080 --> 09:10.835
that you could tell me
that would change the way I feel.

09:11.200 --> 09:13.157
[MOUTHING]

09:15.040 --> 09:16.360
Go on.

09:19.320 --> 09:22.233
I kill...

09:22.720 --> 09:25.360
I murd...

09:27.160 --> 09:29.117
I kill... Oh, I can't.

09:29.320 --> 09:34.634
Burt, sweetheart,
this doesn't have
to be so difficult.

09:34.840 --> 09:39.153
No matter what you say,
no matter what you have
done, I will love you.

09:39.360 --> 09:40.953
That's what you think.

09:41.880 --> 09:43.599
Go on now.

09:48.520 --> 09:50.432
I killed your first husband.

10:07.000 --> 10:09.276
I killed your first husband.

10:13.920 --> 10:15.320
Oh, my God.

10:15.760 --> 10:17.513
[WHIMPERS]

10:21.680 --> 10:23.637
[♪♪♪]

10:29.720 --> 10:31.871
Are you all right?

10:35.600 --> 10:39.640
Boy, oh, boy,
I wish my cardiologist
could have seen me.

10:41.600 --> 10:43.637
I didn't mean to rush you,

10:43.840 --> 10:46.116
but my daughter is coming home.

10:46.320 --> 10:48.391
You know, I didn't think I could.

10:48.600 --> 10:50.193
I didn't think I remembered.

10:50.400 --> 10:52.312
You didn't remember much.

10:54.360 --> 10:56.079
I hope you had
a nice evening, Ingrid.

10:56.280 --> 11:00.194
How can you even ask, Anthony?

11:00.400 --> 11:05.270
Why, you are probably
the most intelligent, fascinating

11:05.480 --> 11:10.555
and gentle man I've met
since... Ingmar Bergman.

11:10.800 --> 11:12.359
Ahh!

11:13.240 --> 11:15.277
Bye-bye, Tony.

11:24.760 --> 11:25.796
Was that the judge?

11:26.000 --> 11:27.320
What, dear?

11:27.520 --> 11:31.799
Judge Petrillo.
That was Judge Petrillo.

11:32.040 --> 11:33.872
[GIGGLING]

11:35.640 --> 11:38.394
Looks like the judge,
doesn't he?

11:38.600 --> 11:40.796
You're trying to fix the trial,
aren't you?

11:41.000 --> 11:42.719
What are you talking about?

11:42.920 --> 11:46.038
You're dating him
so that you can convince
him to hang my mother.

11:46.240 --> 11:48.471
I'm your mother.
You know what I mean.

11:48.680 --> 11:53.596
Well, it just so happens that
I am enormously attracted to him.

11:53.800 --> 11:58.591
When I saw him up there
in the court, I just couldn't
take my eyes off him.

11:58.800 --> 12:00.359
Bull.

12:00.600 --> 12:03.354
What does it mean, this "bull"?

12:04.440 --> 12:06.113
It means you're lying.

12:06.320 --> 12:07.800
You're trying to fix the trial.

12:08.000 --> 12:09.559
How can you do that to her?

12:09.760 --> 12:12.320
Because I hate her.

12:13.080 --> 12:14.434
She's never done
anything to you.

12:14.640 --> 12:16.518
She took you away from me.

12:16.720 --> 12:18.712
That wasn't her.
That was my grandmother.

12:18.920 --> 12:22.038
And then I was sent off
to Ecuador, of all places,

12:22.240 --> 12:24.357
when she knew,
coming from Sweden,

12:24.560 --> 12:27.234
how the heat would affect me.

12:28.480 --> 12:31.279
You said you came here for me
and now you've got me,

12:31.480 --> 12:33.233
so why can't you
leave them alone?

12:33.440 --> 12:35.716
Because it's not enough.

12:35.920 --> 12:38.480
I want to see them all suffer.

12:38.680 --> 12:42.754
Actually, I'd like to see
them all drop dead.

12:42.960 --> 12:45.680
But I'll settle for suffering.

12:45.880 --> 12:48.270
Oh, I hate them.

12:48.480 --> 12:49.675
Well, I'm one of them.

12:49.880 --> 12:51.917
Oh, no, you're not.

12:53.360 --> 12:54.953
Yes, I am.

12:55.160 --> 12:57.800
And you hate them
more than you love me.

12:58.240 --> 13:00.152
Think about it.

13:00.360 --> 13:02.716
[♪♪♪]

13:06.200 --> 13:07.200
[DOORBELL RINGS]

13:07.360 --> 13:09.431
TIM: Ma?
Timothy.

13:10.400 --> 13:11.550
Oh, Tim!

13:11.760 --> 13:13.114
Ma.

13:14.400 --> 13:16.869
How are you, Ma?
Good. Good.

13:17.080 --> 13:19.276
Good to see you.
Come on in.

13:19.480 --> 13:22.279
Oh, I cooked you
everything that you love.

13:22.480 --> 13:23.480
Lasagne?

13:23.640 --> 13:25.632
Oh, lasagne's just
the beginning.

13:27.560 --> 13:29.597
I need to talk to you, Ma.
Yeah, sure.

13:29.800 --> 13:32.474
I got a problem.
Oh, I love it.

13:32.680 --> 13:34.672
People come to priests
with their problems.

13:34.880 --> 13:38.078
And look, a priest
comes to his mother.

13:38.840 --> 13:41.036
I felt I ought to let you know
what was going on.

13:41.240 --> 13:43.391
Yeah, sure.

13:43.600 --> 13:45.910
Of course, tell your mother.

13:46.120 --> 13:48.476
There's a girl.
Where?

13:49.360 --> 13:52.194
No, Ma. There's a girl
and I keep thinking about her.

13:52.440 --> 13:53.840
[SPEAKS IN ITALIAN]

13:55.760 --> 13:57.274
I can't get her out of my mind.

13:58.040 --> 13:59.599
It's a test.

13:59.800 --> 14:02.156
He's giving you a test.

14:02.360 --> 14:05.000
Don't you know a test
when you see one?

14:07.160 --> 14:09.959
No, Ma. It's not a test.

14:11.200 --> 14:13.351
I'm thinking about
leaving the priesthood.

14:13.560 --> 14:16.792
You know, I finally saw
that <i>Star Wars</i> film they
were all raving about.

14:17.000 --> 14:18.514
I don't know, in my day,

14:18.720 --> 14:21.110
they got a leading man,
it was Clark Gable.

14:21.320 --> 14:24.438
Today they got a little
machine that goes, "boop!"

14:24.640 --> 14:26.632
Ma, Ma, did you hear
what I said?

14:26.840 --> 14:28.115
I mean, frankly,
I could have stayed home

14:28.320 --> 14:30.835
and looked at
my upright vacuum cleaner.

14:31.040 --> 14:33.316
Did you hear me?
I'm sorry. I'm getting a little old.

14:33.520 --> 14:34.670
I don't hear so good.

14:34.880 --> 14:36.553
I said I was thinking
about leaving...

14:36.760 --> 14:40.720
I mean, not only is my hearing bad,
but my heart is very weak.

14:40.920 --> 14:44.834
I mean, the slightest shock,
and it could kill me.

14:45.040 --> 14:47.032
Otherwise I'm fine.

14:47.640 --> 14:49.279
I said I was thinking
about leaving...

14:49.480 --> 14:52.359
I heard what you said.
You're thinking about
leaving the priesthood.

14:52.560 --> 14:53.560
Yes.

14:54.480 --> 14:57.154
Okay. Fine.

14:57.920 --> 14:59.513
Ma.

15:01.080 --> 15:02.719
What else can I do?

15:03.600 --> 15:05.159
I think I'm in love.

15:05.360 --> 15:08.910
Fine. I'd like
the coffin closed, please.

15:10.080 --> 15:11.639
Please, Ma.

15:11.840 --> 15:15.151
I came here because
I need some help,
some understanding.

15:15.360 --> 15:18.910
Sorry. All I can
give you is lasagne.

15:20.280 --> 15:23.239
Sometimes priests are
wrong about their calling.

15:23.440 --> 15:24.920
I didn't break my vows.

15:25.120 --> 15:26.918
My superiors understand.

15:27.120 --> 15:28.839
And God will forgive me.

15:30.560 --> 15:31.994
Fine.

15:32.600 --> 15:35.160
If he wants to forgive you,
let him.

15:38.960 --> 15:40.633
I won't.

15:42.880 --> 15:44.837
[♪♪♪]

15:48.160 --> 15:50.311
Mrs. Tate, think, think.

15:50.520 --> 15:52.432
Who might the surprise
witness be?

15:52.640 --> 15:57.920
Oh, Mr. Mallu. If I thought of it,
It would ruin Mr. Franklin's surprise.

15:58.720 --> 16:01.838
Benson, every morning
it's the same thing.

16:02.040 --> 16:04.032
I ask for poached eggs.
I get scrambled.

16:04.240 --> 16:05.993
I ask for shirred eggs.
I get scrambled.

16:06.200 --> 16:08.157
I ask for sunny-side up.
I get scrambled.

16:08.360 --> 16:09.555
I never get what I want.

16:09.760 --> 16:12.070
Why don't you ask for scrambled?

16:12.920 --> 16:15.310
Benson, I will not eat these eggs.

16:16.200 --> 16:17.236
JESSICA:
Benson?

16:17.440 --> 16:20.239
Would you fix some eggs
for Mr. Mallu, please?

16:20.440 --> 16:21.680
Certainly.
How do you like them?

16:21.720 --> 16:22.949
Poached.

16:26.080 --> 16:28.072
All right, Benson,
I'll have scrambled.

16:28.280 --> 16:29.794
Mrs. Tate, think.

16:30.000 --> 16:31.957
Who would say
something bad about you?

16:32.480 --> 16:33.800
Bessie Stevens.

16:34.000 --> 16:35.912
You see, in the seventh grade,

16:36.120 --> 16:38.430
Bessie Stevens had braids
down to her waist,

16:38.640 --> 16:41.235
and I cut them off
to use them to be Pocahontas.

16:42.280 --> 16:45.193
No, no, Mrs. Tate.
It is not Bessie Stevens.

16:45.400 --> 16:47.312
Then it's Robert Corwin.

16:47.760 --> 16:48.796
Robert Corwin.

16:49.000 --> 16:50.673
In the 10th grade,
Robert Corwin...

16:50.880 --> 16:52.792
She thinks we're playing
<i>This is Your Life.</i>

16:54.000 --> 16:56.720
Mrs. Tate, who are
your enemies now?

16:56.920 --> 16:59.640
Enemies? Enemies, sir?

16:59.840 --> 17:03.470
How about Hitler
and Mussolini for starters?

17:04.520 --> 17:05.641
JESSICA:
Good morning, Daddy.

17:05.800 --> 17:07.837
Hi.
Eggs, Major?

17:08.040 --> 17:09.520
Thank you. Yup.

17:09.720 --> 17:11.837
Benson, what about me?

17:12.040 --> 17:14.999
What about you?
Do I have to make them myself?

17:21.839 --> 17:24.435
Mother, I'm not feeling too well.
I've got a sore throat.

17:24.640 --> 17:28.031
Oh, dear. I'm afraid you'll have
to cancel court this morning.

17:28.240 --> 17:30.516
I have to take Billy
to the paediatrician.

17:30.720 --> 17:33.189
Mrs. Tate,
you can't cancel court.

17:33.400 --> 17:35.119
Mom, I don't wanna
go to the doctor.

17:35.320 --> 17:37.880
You have to
go to the doctor.
You have a cold.

17:38.080 --> 17:40.834
You can't take him to the doctor.
You have to go to court.

17:41.040 --> 17:42.918
I'll take him.

17:44.560 --> 17:46.677
The boy's sick.

17:47.200 --> 17:49.237
Heal the cough.

17:49.480 --> 17:51.437
[♪♪♪]

17:52.720 --> 17:55.519
And now, Mrs. Tate, before
you complete your testimony,

17:55.720 --> 17:59.236
tell me, did you or did you not
kill Peter Campbell?

17:59.440 --> 18:02.353
Do you know you have
asked me that question
six times?

18:02.560 --> 18:03.835
Yes.

18:04.040 --> 18:06.236
But this time
I want the jury to hear.

18:06.440 --> 18:09.000
Did you or did you not
kill Peter Campbell?

18:09.200 --> 18:13.035
Seven. He has asked me
that question seven times.

18:13.240 --> 18:18.360
Do you wonder how this man
ever got out of law school?

18:21.640 --> 18:22.994
No.
No, what?

18:23.200 --> 18:25.874
No, I didn't kill
Peter Campbell.

18:26.080 --> 18:27.673
Thank you, Mrs. Tate.

18:27.880 --> 18:30.952
And now, in your lifetime,
have you ever killed anything?

18:31.160 --> 18:32.560
No. Never.

18:32.760 --> 18:36.959
Unless you want to count the times
that I accidentally stepped on ants.

18:37.160 --> 18:38.196
I object.

18:38.400 --> 18:40.517
Mr. Franklin, you cannot
help stepping on them.

18:40.720 --> 18:42.234
They're so tiny.

18:43.200 --> 18:44.839
But I never put out
ant poisoning

18:45.040 --> 18:47.600
and I never deliberately
tried to kill them.

18:48.320 --> 18:50.232
I'm sorry.

18:54.720 --> 18:57.280
So you mean to say that
you've never killed anything,

18:57.480 --> 18:59.039
not even a bug?
That's right.

18:59.880 --> 19:02.440
Ask Chester.
His suits are full of holes

19:02.640 --> 19:05.633
because I will not use
moth balls.

19:06.720 --> 19:08.598
Thank you, Mrs. Tate.

19:08.800 --> 19:10.314
Holes in his sweaters.

19:10.520 --> 19:12.432
Thank you.
Holes in his socks.

19:12.640 --> 19:13.994
That's enough, Mrs. Tate.

19:14.200 --> 19:15.998
Holes in his shorts.

19:16.200 --> 19:18.510
But they're not moths,
they're flies.

19:19.160 --> 19:20.833
Get it?

19:25.200 --> 19:27.112
No more questions.

19:27.320 --> 19:28.959
Flies in his shorts?

19:29.160 --> 19:31.720
Ever try to use a pair
without one?

19:32.760 --> 19:37.312
Now, Mrs. Tate,
did you or did you not
kill Peter Campbell?

19:37.520 --> 19:39.830
Weren't you listening?

19:40.040 --> 19:42.509
What is the matter with you men?

19:42.720 --> 19:47.556
Objection, Your Honour.
The counsel is badgering my client
in an obvious attempt to stall.

19:47.760 --> 19:51.197
Because he cannot produce
the surprise witness
he's promised for today.

19:51.400 --> 19:52.470
I can too.
Oh, yeah?

19:52.680 --> 19:54.041
Yeah.
Mr. Franklin, how much longer

19:54.240 --> 19:55.356
do we have to wait?

19:55.560 --> 19:58.155
Ah, just a few more minutes.
I object, Your Honour.

19:58.360 --> 20:00.636
The court has indulged
the counsel long enough.

20:00.840 --> 20:03.674
One wonders if he even has
a surprise witness at all.

20:03.880 --> 20:07.112
Well, Mr. Franklin,
the court will allow you
a minute or two longer.

20:07.320 --> 20:08.549
But that's all.
Thank you.

20:08.760 --> 20:09.830
Everybody relax.

20:11.960 --> 20:13.679
Have I got time
to go to the bathroom?

20:13.880 --> 20:16.156
Don't take anything to read.

20:21.440 --> 20:22.440
Hi.

20:23.080 --> 20:25.470
You haven't changed your
mind about this weekend,
have you?

20:25.680 --> 20:27.114
Listen, Carol, I...
Oh, come on.

20:27.320 --> 20:28.993
Now, I got us
a two-bedroom cottage.

20:29.200 --> 20:31.271
We're going as friends,
remember?

20:31.480 --> 20:33.756
Okay. Friends.

20:38.680 --> 20:41.115
You're going away
with him for a weekend?

20:41.320 --> 20:43.516
That's right.
But he's a homosexual.

20:43.720 --> 20:44.720
That's right.

20:44.920 --> 20:47.151
And he might come back
a homosexual.

20:47.360 --> 20:49.238
But if he does,

20:49.440 --> 20:52.751
he is sure gonna have
something to compare it to.

20:55.840 --> 20:57.832
All right, Mr. Franklin,
your time is up.

20:58.040 --> 21:00.714
Now, I'm sorry,
but I'm gonna have to...

21:01.200 --> 21:04.352
Your Honour, I would like to
call to the stand at this time

21:04.560 --> 21:06.074
Mrs. Sheila Fine.

21:07.840 --> 21:11.038
Who's that?
Mrs. Fine. Pay attention.

21:14.080 --> 21:17.630
You're going away
for the weekend to
the beach with a girl?

21:17.840 --> 21:21.072
Wonderful. I hope
she takes a book to read.

21:21.640 --> 21:23.074
That's fantastic.

21:23.280 --> 21:24.396
Be seated.

21:24.600 --> 21:26.034
State your name
and address, please.

21:26.240 --> 21:29.392
Sheila Fine.
5093 Rockridge Road.

21:29.600 --> 21:30.954
But call first.

21:34.000 --> 21:37.755
Mrs. Fine, did you know
Peter Campbell, the deceased?

21:37.960 --> 21:39.553
Did I know him?

21:40.240 --> 21:42.630
Do you know what
this jerk did to my life?

21:44.000 --> 21:47.232
He comes into my house
where I'm sitting with my husband,

21:47.440 --> 21:51.639
and he says I have to testify
since I was having an affair
with Peter Campbell.

21:51.840 --> 21:53.433
My husband called his lawyer,

21:53.640 --> 21:56.075
grabbed his girlfriend
and flew to Acapulco.

21:56.280 --> 21:59.830
I hope a taco chip gets caught
in his throat and he chokes to death.

22:00.440 --> 22:03.478
Yes, Mr. Franklin,
I knew Peter Campbell.

22:03.680 --> 22:04.796
And how did you know him?

22:05.000 --> 22:06.639
Lying down.

22:07.720 --> 22:08.790
I see.

22:09.000 --> 22:12.232
And where was the last time
you saw the defendant, Mrs. Tate?

22:12.440 --> 22:15.831
In Peter Campbell's bathroom
the day he was murdered.

22:16.080 --> 22:18.276
[CROWD GASPS]

22:18.520 --> 22:21.354
And did you hear
the defendant say anything?

22:21.560 --> 22:24.281
Your Honour, this line
of questioning is an
obvious delaying tactic...

22:24.400 --> 22:28.235
If it please the court,
I will explain my line
of questioning.

22:28.440 --> 22:30.079
Your Honour, up until now,

22:30.280 --> 22:33.239
there has been only one element
missing from the state's case.

22:33.440 --> 22:35.875
We have shown
the motive for the defendant.

22:36.080 --> 22:38.834
The murder weapons were found
in the defendant's possession.

22:39.040 --> 22:41.600
And now we are about
to hear testimony

22:41.800 --> 22:44.554
that, once and for all,
will remove all doubt

22:44.760 --> 22:48.197
and clearly establish
the guilt of the accused.

22:48.960 --> 22:53.352
Mrs. Fine, what did you hear
Jessica Tate say to Peter Campbell

22:53.560 --> 22:56.200
on the very day of the murder?

22:56.400 --> 23:01.475
I heard her say to him,
"I'm so angry, I could kill you."

23:01.720 --> 23:04.280
[CROWD CHATTERING]

23:04.480 --> 23:06.278
The prosecution rests.

23:08.960 --> 23:10.917
[♪♪♪]

23:19.840 --> 23:23.151
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Did Walter really walk out</i>
<i>on Eunice forever?</i>

23:23.360 --> 23:25.875
<i>Did he also leave her</i>
<i>with the restaurant bill?</i>

23:26.080 --> 23:29.630
<i>Now that Mary has learned that Burt</i>
<i>killed her first husband, Johnny,</i>

23:29.840 --> 23:32.480
<i>what does Mary think</i>
<i>of her second husband, Burt?</i>

23:32.680 --> 23:35.559
<i>Now that Corinne has</i>
<i>walked out on two mothers,</i>

23:35.760 --> 23:38.992
<i>does that make her ineligible</i>
<i>for the Daughter of the Year award?</i>

23:39.200 --> 23:43.513
<i>Has Mrs. Fine's testimony convinced</i>
<i>the jury that Jessica is guilty?</i>

23:43.720 --> 23:45.518
<i>Is Jessica guilty?</i>

23:45.720 --> 23:47.313
<i>These questions, and many others,</i>

23:47.520 --> 23:50.558
<i>will be answered on</i>
<i>next week's episode of</i> Soap.

23:50.760 --> 23:52.717
